## Session 2: CSS Box Model & Layout

Every HTML element is a rectangular box. The CSS box model defines how boxes are sized and how they interact with each other.

### The Box Model

```css
/* Default: content-box — width applies to content only */
.box-content {
  width: 200px;    /* content width */
  padding: 20px;   /* adds to total: 240px */
  border: 2px solid; /* adds to total: 244px */
  margin: 10px;    /* space outside the element */
  /* Total width rendered: 244px */
}

/* border-box — width includes padding and border */
*, *::before, *::after { box-sizing: border-box; } /* always set this */
.box-border {
  width: 200px;    /* total width including padding + border */
  padding: 20px;   /* content width is now 160px (200 - 20 - 20) */
  border: 2px solid;
  /* Total width rendered: 200px — predictable! */
}

/* Block vs Inline */
div { display: block; }   /* full width, new line before and after */
span { display: inline; }  /* width wraps content, no new line */
/* Width/height have no effect on inline elements */
```

### Flexbox

```css
/* Container properties */
.flex-container {
  display: flex;
  flex-direction: row;         /* row | row-reverse | column | column-reverse */
  justify-content: space-between; /* main axis distribution */
  align-items: center;         /* cross axis alignment */
  flex-wrap: wrap;             /* allow wrapping */
  gap: 1rem;                   /* space between items */
}

/* Item properties */
.flex-item {
  flex-grow: 1;    /* how much extra space to take */
  flex-shrink: 1;  /* how much to shrink if needed */
  flex-basis: 0%;  /* initial size before growth/shrink */
  flex: 1;         /* shorthand: grow=1, shrink=1, basis=0 */
  align-self: flex-start; /* override container's align-items for this item */
  order: 2;        /* change visual order without changing DOM order */
}

/* Common patterns */
/* Center anything */
.center { display: flex; justify-content: center; align-items: center; }

/* Sticky footer */
.page { display: flex; flex-direction: column; min-height: 100vh; }
.page main { flex: 1; }

/* Space between items, vertically centered */
.toolbar { display: flex; justify-content: space-between; align-items: center; }
```

### CSS Grid

```css
/* Explicit grid */
.grid {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: 250px 1fr 1fr; /* sidebar + 2 equal columns */
  grid-template-rows: auto 1fr auto;    /* header, content, footer */
  gap: 1rem;
}

/* Responsive grid — no media queries needed */
.auto-grid {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(250px, 1fr));
  /* Creates as many 250px+ columns as fit, expanding to fill */
}

/* Named areas */
.layout {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-areas:
    'header header'
    'sidebar main'
    'footer footer';
  grid-template-columns: 250px 1fr;
  grid-template-rows: auto 1fr auto;
  min-height: 100vh;
}
.header  { grid-area: header; }
.sidebar { grid-area: sidebar; }
.main    { grid-area: main; }
.footer  { grid-area: footer; }

/* Spanning cells */
.feature-card {
  grid-column: 1 / 3;  /* span columns 1-2 */
  grid-row: 2 / 4;     /* span rows 2-3 */
}
```

### Positioning

```css
.relative-parent {
  position: relative; /* establishes positioning context */
  /* Used as anchor for absolute children */
}

.absolute-child {
  position: absolute; /* removed from normal flow */
  top: 0; right: 0;  /* relative to nearest positioned ancestor */
  /* width/height must be explicit or set by content */
}

.sticky-header {
  position: sticky;
  top: 0; /* sticks when it reaches 0px from viewport top */
  z-index: 100;
}

/* Common: overlay and tooltip positioning */
.tooltip-container {
  position: relative;
  display: inline-block;
}
.tooltip {
  position: absolute;
  bottom: 100%; /* above the container */
  left: 50%;
  transform: translateX(-50%); /* center horizontally */
  white-space: nowrap;
}
```

### Interview Insight

"When would you use Grid vs Flexbox?" — Flexbox is one-dimensional (row OR column). Use it for: navigation bars, tool bars, centering, wrapping lists of cards. Grid is two-dimensional (rows AND columns). Use it for: page layouts, dashboard grids, magazine layouts, any 2D arrangement. They are often used together: Grid for the macro layout, Flexbox within individual cells.

