## Session 3: Responsive Design

```mermaid
graph LR
    A((A)) --> B((B))
    A --> C((C))
    B --> D((D))
    C --> D
    D --> E((E))
```


Responsive design means a single HTML document that provides an optimal experience across all screen sizes — from 320px mobile to 2560px wide monitor.

### Mobile-First Methodology

Start with styles for the smallest screen, then use `min-width` media queries to add complexity for larger screens. This ensures the minimum viable CSS ships to mobile devices.

```css
/* Mobile first: base styles (no media query = all screens) */
.container {
  width: 100%;
  padding: 0 1rem;
}

.nav-links {
  display: none; /* hidden on mobile */
}

.hamburger {
  display: block; /* shown on mobile */
}

/* Tablet: 768px and up */
@media (min-width: 48rem) { /* 768px / 16 = 48rem */
  .container {
    max-width: 720px;
    margin: 0 auto;
  }

  .nav-links {
    display: flex;
    gap: 1rem;
  }

  .hamburger {
    display: none;
  }
}

/* Desktop: 1024px and up */
@media (min-width: 64rem) {
  .container { max-width: 1200px; }
}

/* Large Desktop: 1440px and up */
@media (min-width: 90rem) {
  .container { max-width: 1400px; }
}
```

### Fluid Typography with clamp()

```css
/* clamp(minimum, preferred, maximum) */
:root {
  /* Text scales smoothly from 1rem at 320px to 1.25rem at 1440px */
  --font-size-base: clamp(1rem, 0.875rem + 0.625vw, 1.25rem);

  /* Heading: 2rem at 320px → 4rem at 1440px */
  --font-size-h1: clamp(2rem, 1.5rem + 2.5vw, 4rem);

  /* Spacing that scales with viewport */
  --spacing-section: clamp(3rem, 5vw, 8rem);
}

body { font-size: var(--font-size-base); }
h1   { font-size: var(--font-size-h1); }
.section { padding-block: var(--spacing-section); }
```

### Responsive Images

```html
<!-- srcset: browser chooses best size for screen density -->
<img
  src="/image-800.jpg"
  srcset="/image-400.jpg 400w, /image-800.jpg 800w, /image-1600.jpg 1600w"
  sizes="(max-width: 768px) 100vw, (max-width: 1024px) 50vw, 800px"
  alt="Descriptive alt text"
  width="800"
  height="600"
  loading="lazy"
>

<!-- picture: art direction — different images at different sizes -->
<picture>
  <source media="(max-width: 767px)" srcset="/hero-mobile.jpg">
  <source media="(max-width: 1023px)" srcset="/hero-tablet.jpg">
  <img src="/hero-desktop.jpg" alt="Hero image">
</picture>
```

### Viewport Units and Logical Properties

```css
/* Viewport units */
.hero { height: 100svh; } /* 100% small viewport height — mobile-safe */
.sidebar { width: 25vw; } /* 25% of viewport width */
.banner { font-size: 5vw; } /* fluid, but prefer clamp() for controlled limits */

/* Logical properties — direction-agnostic, RTL-safe */
.card {
  padding-inline: 1rem;  /* padding-left + padding-right */
  padding-block: 2rem;   /* padding-top + padding-bottom */
  margin-inline: auto;   /* margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto → center */
  border-inline-start: 4px solid; /* left border in LTR, right border in RTL */
}

/* Container queries — responsive based on PARENT width, not viewport */
.card-container { container-type: inline-size; }

@container (min-width: 400px) {
  .card { flex-direction: row; } /* card goes horizontal when container is wide enough */
}
```

### Breakpoint Strategy

Use content-driven breakpoints, not device breakpoints. The breakpoint is where the content looks broken, not where a specific device ends.

```css
/* Common breakpoints (rem-based for accessibility — respects user font size) */
/* 480px = 30rem  — large phone landscape */
/* 768px = 48rem  — tablet */
/* 1024px = 64rem — desktop */
/* 1440px = 90rem — wide desktop */
```

