## Session 7: Browser Rendering

Understanding how the browser turns HTML and CSS into pixels enables you to write performant code and diagnose rendering bottlenecks.

### The Critical Rendering Path

```
1. Parse HTML          → DOM tree
2. Parse CSS           → CSSOM tree  
3. DOM + CSSOM         → Render Tree (only visible nodes)
4. Layout              → Calculate box dimensions and positions
5. Paint               → Fill pixels (text, colors, images, borders)
6. Composite           → Layer GPU composition (transforms, opacity)

JavaScript can modify the DOM and CSSOM at any step, potentially triggering the path again.
```

### Render Blocking Resources

```html
<!-- CSS is render-blocking by default — browser won't paint until CSS parses -->
<link rel="stylesheet" href="styles.css"> <!-- blocks rendering -->

<!-- Non-critical CSS: load async, swap in when ready -->
<link rel="preload" href="print.css" as="style" onload="this.rel='stylesheet'">

<!-- Critical CSS: inline in <head> for fastest first paint -->
<style>
  /* Only above-the-fold styles */
  body { margin: 0; font-family: system-ui; }
  .hero { height: 100vh; display: flex; align-items: center; }
</style>

<!-- JS blocks HTML parsing when it can modify the DOM -->
<script src="app.js"></script>          <!-- blocking -->
<script src="analytics.js" defer></script>    <!-- deferred: runs after parse -->
<script src="widget.js" async></script>       <!-- async: runs when downloaded -->
```

### Reflow vs Repaint vs Composite

| Operation | What triggers it | Cost |
|-----------|-----------------|------|
| Reflow (Layout) | Changing width, height, font-size, adding/removing elements | Highest — recalculates all affected elements |
| Repaint | Changing color, background, box-shadow (no geometry change) | Medium — re-paints affected pixels |
| Composite | Changing transform, opacity | Lowest — GPU only |

```javascript
// Triggering forced synchronous layout (layout thrashing)
// AVOID: read-write-read-write in a loop
const boxes = document.querySelectorAll('.box');
boxes.forEach(box => {
  const width = box.offsetWidth;           // READS layout (forces reflow)
  box.style.width = (width * 1.1) + 'px'; // WRITES layout
  // Each iteration forces a sync layout because write invalidates, then read forces recalc
});

// CORRECT: batch reads, then batch writes
const widths = [...boxes].map(box => box.offsetWidth); // batch reads
boxes.forEach((box, i) => {
  box.style.width = (widths[i] * 1.1) + 'px'; // batch writes
});

// Or use requestAnimationFrame for animations
function animate() {
  element.style.transform = `translateX(${position}px)`;
  position += 1;
  requestAnimationFrame(animate);
}
```

### Properties that Cause Reflow (avoid animating these)

width, height, padding, margin, border, top, left, right, bottom, font-size, line-height, white-space, overflow, min-height, display, flex-basis.

### Promoting Elements to Their Own Compositor Layer

```css
/* will-change: hint browser to create a GPU layer in advance */
.animated-element {
  will-change: transform; /* tells browser to pre-create a layer */
  /* only add when you KNOW animation is about to happen */
  /* overuse wastes memory */
}

/* Legacy: force layer creation */
.layer-hack {
  transform: translateZ(0); /* triggers layer creation */
  /* prefer will-change — it's the semantic way */
}
```

